 74-77 "go back" to continuum bins. why?
 Here is where the card tells the code how to construct transfer couplings TO/FROM continuum states.
 Form factors 2-59 defined the projectile continuum itself, while form factors 74-77 tell the transfer operators how to CONNECT them. 
 
 using partition 1 and 3 
 74 75 1 3 1 3   1 2 2 0.0 1 2.0 4 17  0 -5.0228  4  3  0-90-10.0256 	|
 76    1 3 1 3   1 2 2 0.0 1 2.0 3 17  0 -1.9651  4  3  0-90 -3.9102	|

 77    1 3 1 3   1 2 2 0.0 1 2.0 2 17  0 -0.4950 14  3  0-90 -0.9700	|

 I want to, again, explicitly label each of the settings in form factor 77 now that there are extra settings that were deactivated
 in the form factor defining the continuum bin. 

 77          | KN1   | form-factor index
 blank/0     | KN2   | no range; this is just FF #77
 1           | IC1   | first partition involved
 3           | IC2   | second partition involved
 1           | IN    | particle is in projectile side
 3           | KIND  | coupled-core / summed coupled-channel form factor

 blank       | CH1   | no special cluster label
 1           | NN    | node count for this component
 2           | L     | minimum/component orbital angular momentum l = 2
 2           | LMAX  | maximum l included in the coupled sum
 0.0         | SN    | intrinsic spin used in coupled-core construction
 1           | IA    | core state index included in the coupled form factor
 2.0         | JN    | maximum/intermediate j included in the sum
 2           | IB    | composite state index

 17          | KBPOT | (6Li | α+d) internal potential
 0           | KRPOT | transfer potential index; 0 means use KBPOT
 -0.4950     | BE    | continuum bin midpoint energy
 14          | ISC   | continuum weighting prescription
 3           | IPC   | print control
 0           | NFL   | wavefunction file unit
 -90         | NAM   | explicit continuum-bin integration/range control
 -0.9700     | AMPL  | other bin boundary, here upper edge in negative-BE convention
 
 BIG difference being:
   KIND = 0  → simple (L,S)J form factor
   KIND = 3  → summed/coupled-core form factor

  So FF#77 is not just “make one ℓ=2,j=3 bin.” 
  It is using the coupled-channel form-factor machinery to connect continuum pieces in the transfer/coupling sector.


